    body: "If you are 60 or older and writing a resume in 2026, the rules have changed since the last time you looked for work. The paper resume mailed in an envelope is gone. Today, almost every resume is read first by a computer program called an Applicant Tracking System, or ATS. The computer scans your resume for the right words, the right format, and the right structure before a human ever sees it. A resume that worked well in 1995 or 2005 will often get rejected by the computer in 2026, not because you are not qualified, but because the format confuses the software.\n\nThe good news is that a senior-friendly resume in 2026 plays to your strengths. Decades of experience, a long track record of dependability, mentoring younger workers, and steady judgment are valuable to employers who are tired of staff turnover. Companies that hire older workers, including AARP Employer Pledge signers, federal agencies, school districts, hospitals, libraries, and many small businesses, want exactly what you bring. The work is to package your experience in a format the computer can read and a hiring manager can scan in fifteen seconds.\n\nThree things have shifted in resume writing since most people over 60 last wrote one. First, length: a resume in 2026 is usually one or two pages, not three or four, even with thirty years of experience. Employers do not want a full work history; they want the last ten to fifteen years and the highlights of what came before. Second, dates: your year of graduation from college in 1975 or 1982 tells the screener your age and can lead to bias. Most career counselors now suggest dropping graduation years and listing only the degree, the school, and the city. Third, keywords: the ATS computer is looking for words that match the job posting. If the posting says \"customer service,\" your resume must say \"customer service,\" not \"helped clients.\"\n\nThe most important rule for an older worker's resume is to show you are current. A resume full of typewriter-era job titles, no email address, or no mention of any software newer than Microsoft Word 2003 tells the employer you have not kept up. Adding a few modern tools you have actually used (Zoom, Google Docs, Teams, Slack, Canva, ChatGPT, QuickBooks Online) signals that you have moved with the times. You do not need to claim expert skill; familiarity is enough. The steps below walk through writing your 2026 resume from a blank page, using free tools and plain language.",
