    body: "LinkedIn is the largest professional network in the world, with more than one billion members in 2026, and it is also the single most important job-search tool for workers over 60. Roughly 87 percent of recruiters and corporate HR departments search LinkedIn first when looking for candidates, often before they ever post a job publicly. For an older job seeker, LinkedIn solves a problem that paper resumes cannot: it lets you tell your full story, show recommendations from former bosses and coworkers, and make warm connections at companies you want to work for. A well-built LinkedIn profile can bring opportunities to you instead of you chasing them.\n\nMany people over 60 either skip LinkedIn entirely or set up a profile in 2015 and never touched it again. Both are mistakes. An empty or out-of-date LinkedIn profile is worse than no profile because it signals that the candidate has not kept up with the times. The good news is that fixing a LinkedIn profile is a one-evening project, and the platform is free for job seekers. You only pay if you choose the optional premium account ($30 to $40 a month), which is useful for active searches but not required for most people.\n\nThe biggest concern older job seekers have about LinkedIn is age bias. The rules of the platform require listing some employment history, but you do not have to list every job back to 1976. The widely accepted convention is to list the last 15 to 20 years of jobs in detail, then a single \"Earlier Experience\" line summarizing earlier roles. You also do not have to list graduation years; LinkedIn lets you enter dates as \"start year to present\" or omit dates on the education section entirely. A clean recent profile photo, modern language in your About section, and a few mentions of current tools (Zoom, Teams, Slack, AI tools, modern software) signal to recruiters that you have stayed current.\n\nLinkedIn rewards activity. Profiles that get viewed and engaged with show up higher in recruiter searches. Spending 15 minutes a week posting a comment, sharing an article, or congratulating a former colleague keeps your profile near the top of search results. You do not have to write long original posts or share personal opinions. A simple comment on someone else's update (\"Great point about customer retention\") is enough activity to keep your profile fresh. The steps below walk through setting up or refreshing your profile, finding the right people, and starting conversations that lead to interviews.",
